@node Parsing and detection
@section Parsing and detection

@findex color-extras-parse-color
@findex color-extras-looking-at-rgb
@findex color-extras-looking-at-hsl-scaled
@findex color-extras-looking-at-color
The function @code{color-extras-parse-color} accepts a color string and
returns either a HEX string (without the leading @samp{#}) or an HSL list
of three numbers, depending on which pattern matches.  Pass a non-nil
STRING argument to get the HSL result as a formatted string instead of
a list.

Three companion functions detect colors at point:
@code{color-extras-looking-at-rgb} returns the six-digit HEX string (or
@code{nil}), @code{color-extras-looking-at-hsl-scaled} returns the HSL color as
a list or formatted string, and @code{color-extras-looking-at-color} tries
HEX first and falls back to HSL@.  These are the building blocks used
by the interactive commands (@ref{Conversion}).

@node HSL formatting
@section HSL formatting

@findex color-extras-hsl-split
@findex color-extras-hsl-to-string
@findex color-extras-format-hsl
The function @code{color-extras-hsl-split} extracts hue, saturation, and
luminance from the current regexp match data (assuming a match against
@code{color-extras-hsl-scaled-pattern}) and returns them as a list of three
numbers.  @code{color-extras-hsl-to-string} takes such a list and formats
it as @samp{"H, S%, L%"}, rounding each component to the nearest integer.
@code{color-extras-format-hsl} is a convenience wrapper that returns either
the list or the string form depending on its STRING argument.

@node Color space conversions
@section Color space conversions

@findex color-extras-hex-to-hsl
@findex color-extras-hsl-to-hex
@findex color-extras-hex-to-rgb
@findex color-extras-rgb-to-hex
These four functions form the conversion core of the package.

@code{color-extras-hex-to-rgb} converts a HEX string (supporting 3-, 4-,
6-, and 8-digit forms) to a list of three RGB floats in the range
0.0--1.0.  @code{color-extras-rgb-to-hex} does the reverse, accepting
three integers in the range 0--255 and returning a @samp{#RRGGBB} string.

@code{color-extras-hex-to-hsl} converts a HEX string to an HSL list.  When
the optional RESCALE argument is non-nil, hue is scaled to 0--360 and
saturation and luminance to 0--100; otherwise all three values are in
the 0.0--1.0 range.  @code{color-extras-hsl-to-hex} performs the inverse
transformation, with the same RESCALE convention.

@node Rescaling helpers
@section Rescaling helpers

@findex color-extras-hsl-rescale
@findex color-extras-hsl-maybe-rescale
The function @code{color-extras-hsl-rescale} converts HSL values between
the normalized (0.0--1.0) and scaled (0--360 / 0--100) ranges.  The
OPERATION argument should be @code{*} (to go from normalized to scaled) or
@code{/} (to go from scaled to normalized).
@code{color-extras-hsl-maybe-rescale} is a conditional wrapper that only
rescales when its RESCALE argument is non-nil.

@node Embark integration
@chapter Embark integration

@findex color-extras-embark-color-finder
When the @samp{embark} package is loaded, @samp{color-extras.el} registers a
target finder, @code{color-extras-embark-color-finder}, that recognizes HEX
and HSL color strings at point and tags them with the @code{color}
category.

A dedicated keymap, @code{color-extras-embark-map}, is associated with this
category.  It provides two actions:

@table @asis
@item @samp{c}
@code{color-extras-convert} --- convert between HEX and HSL
(@ref{Conversion}).
@item @samp{w}
@code{embark-copy-as-kill} --- copy the color string to the kill
ring.
@end table

This means you can invoke @samp{embark-act} with point on any color value
and immediately convert it or copy it.

